.nh
.TH gloat-install -- Installing Gloat
Gloat has \fBzero dependencies\fP - everything installs automatically on first
use.

.PP
There are two main ways to get started: the one-line installer or cloning the
repository and sourcing the \fB\&.rc\fR file.

.SH One-Line Installer
Install \fBgloat\fR (or \fBglj\fR) to \fB~/.local/bin/\fR with a single command:

.EX
make -f <(curl -sL gloathub.org/make) install
.EE

.PP
Installing \fBgloat\fR clones the gloat repository to \fB~/.local/share/gloat\fR,
creates a symlink at \fB~/.local/bin/gloat\fR, and installs all the required
dependencies automatically.

.PP
Make sure \fB~/.local/bin\fR is in your \fBPATH\fR, then run \fBgloat --help\fR\&.

.PP
\fBOptions:\fP

.EX
# Install to a custom prefix
make -f <(curl -sL gloathub.org/make) install PREFIX=~/.gloat

# Install a specific version
make -f <(curl -sL gloathub.org/make) install VERSION=v0.1.37

# Also install the Glojure glj (prebuilt binary) command
make -f <(curl -sL gloathub.org/make) install-glj

# Uninstall
make -f <(curl -sL gloathub.org/make) uninstall
make -f <(curl -sL gloathub.org/make) uninstall-glj

# Show the installer Makefile rules:
make -f <(curl -sL gloathub.org/make) help
.EE

.PP
.RS

.PP
\fBNote\fP: This installation method does not enable gloat shell completion.
For that, run \fBsource <(gloat --complete bash)\fR (or \fBfish\fR/\fBzsh\fR) in your
shell's rc file after installation.

.RE

.SH Clone and Setup
For Bash, Fish or Zsh:

.EX
git clone https://github.com/gloathub/gloat
source gloat/.rc
gloat --help
.EE

.PP
The \fBsource gloat/.rc\fR command adds the \fBgloat\fR command to your PATH, enables
the \fBman gloat\fR help and sets up \fBgloat\fR tab completion.

.PP
On first run, Gloat will automatically install all required tools (Go, Glojure,
YAMLScript, Babashka, etc) to \fB\&.cache/local/\fR within the project directory.
Just run \fBgloat --help\fR once to complete the setup.

.PP
To make Gloat available permanently, simply add this to your shell's rc file
(\fB~/.bashrc\fR, \fB~/.fishrc\fR or \fB~/.zshrc\fR):

.EX
source /path/to/gloat/.rc
.EE

.PP
Yes, that command and \fB\&.rc\fR file actually supports all three shells!
